William DAUGHERTY, aged 43 years, ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> William DAUGHERTY, aged 43 years, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 of Benwood, West Virginia, was instantly killed and Mrs. Steve POLLACK and four year old daughter seriously, probably fatally injured, when a touring car driven by Daugherty went over the narrows, below McMechen, <<<<<<< HEAD at 3:20 oclock Sunday afternoon. The car dropped about 25 feet and then rolled ======= at 3:20 o clock Sunday afternoon. The car dropped about 25 feet and then rolled >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 70 feet down the hillside to the ditch along the B. & O. tracks. Mrs. Pollack sustained a compound fracture of the thigh, two broken fingers and is thought to be internally injured. Her daughter received a fractured skull. Sam VISNICK, his wife and son, the other occupants of the car, were only slightly injured.
Daugherty was found with his head ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Daugherty was found with his head >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 pinned under the fender and resting on the ground and his feet in the car between the steering wheel rod and the seat. Mrs. Pollack and her child were laying in the ditch along side of the car. Visnick, his wife and son fell from the car where it struck last, about 20 feet above the level of the B. & O. tracks before taking its final drop. Visnick lodged against a small tree, and his wife and child rolled on down the hillside.

DAUGHERTY, of Woodsfield, had been an employee of the Hitchman Coal company for probably en or twelve years. He operated on of the machines used in the mining of coal. He and his wife and their three sons, the oldest a young man, resided on South Marshall Street, Benwood. The family opened a restaurant in the room just north of the Midway pharmacy about a week ago. The deceased is also survived by his mother and several brothers who reside in <<<<<<< HEAD Moundsville. Among the brothers are Al, Dinger and Otto DAUGHERTY.

Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs., Jan. 11, 1917
A writer from A writer from >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Summerfield, Ohio to the Zanesville Signal gives the following account of the double tragedy enacted at that place Friday, January 5, 1917. The writer says:
When little Holly WILLIAMS aged ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> When little Holly WILLIAMS aged >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 11, returned to his home here after school Friday afternoon, he found his mother Mrs. Maud WILLIAMS, 50, dead on the floor in the dining room; a few seconds later the child heard the report of a revolver shot in an upper room which resulted ten hours later in the death of his father, Dr. John H. WILLIAMS.
All circumstances surrounding the tragedy indicate that Dr. Williams killed his wife at 3 oclock Friday ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> All circumstances surrounding the tragedy indicate that Dr. Williams killed his wife at 3 o clock Friday >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 afternoon by firing a bullet into her temple. Disordered condition of the furniture of the room point out that Mrs. Williams made a terrible struggle for her life.
Stung by the grief-stricken screams of his young son when he returned from school, and unable to face the accusing eyes of his child, Dr. Williams took his own life at 3:30 oclock with the same weapon which he had used in murdering his wife. Dr. Williams body was ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Stung by the grief-stricken screams of his young son when he returned from school, and unable to face the accusing eyes of his child, Dr. Williams took his own life at 3:30 o clock with the same weapon which he had used in murdering his wife. Dr. Williams body was >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 found in a bedroom in the second story of the house. He died early Saturday morning without regaining consciousness, and leaving no explanation for the double shooting. He was 60 years old.
A 38 caliber revolver was used by ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> A 38 caliber revolver was used by >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Dr. Williams in the shooting. The fact that the physician was at one time confined in a sanitarium for mental derangement leads the authorities to believe that the crime and suicide were committed while Dr. Williams was not mentally responsible for his deeds.
Both Dr. and Mrs. Williams were socially prominent and highly esteemed. Dr. Williams had practiced medicine for over thirty years. He was a mason and a member of the Knights of Pythias. Mrs. Williams was an active member of the ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Both Dr. and Mrs. Williams were socially prominent and highly esteemed. Dr. Williams had practiced medicine for over thirty years. He was a mason and a member of the Knights of Pythias. Mrs. Williams was an active member of the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Summerfield M. E. Church. The eleven-year old son is their only child but Mrs. Williams is also survived by several children by her first husband, Frank REED. They are Miss Hattie REED of Zanesville, Ohio, Mrs. Vivian WARD of Cleveland, Ohio, Ford REED of Jackson, Michigan, Con REED of Salt Lake City, Utah, Rodger REED of Canton, Ohio, Mrs. T. S. BECKER of American Falls, Idaho, Miss Clara REED of Woodsfield and William REED of Summerfield.
Dr. Williams had also been ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Dr. Williams had also been >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 previously married.
Dr. and Mrs. Williams were well known in Woodsfield, Mrs. Williams at one time being a resident here.

Name: John W. ROUSE
======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> John W. ROUSE >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs., Jan. 25, 1917
John W. ROUSE, aged about 65 ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> John W. ROUSE, aged about 65 >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 years, died suddenly at his home in Summerfield Monday, January 22, 1917, forenoon.
He went to his store in the morning ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> He went to his store in the morning >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 as usual and from there to the First National Bank of which he was president. After returning from the bank to his store he began feeling sick and remarked to his partner that he would go home. In a few moments after arriving at his home he died.
Mr. Rouse was a son of the late ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Mr. Rouse was a son of the late >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Mr. and Mrs. Benjamin ROUSE of Hope Ridge and grew to manhood on the farm there. Later he became interested in the mercantile business in Summerfield and was also one of the leading men to establish the First National Bank at that place and has been president from the first organization. He was a splendid business man and because of his honest upright life he enjoyed the respect of all who knew him. He was a member of the Methodist Episcopal Church and Independent Order of Oddfellows. A wife, two daughters are left; Also three brothers, James G. ROUSE and Thomas D. ROUSE of Woodsfield, and W. H. ROUSE and one sister Miss M. Elizabeth ROUSE of Hope Ridge. The funeral was held Wednesday afternoon. Interment at Summerfield, Ohio.

Mr. Brownfield was born in Seneca ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Mr. Brownfield was born in Seneca >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 township, this County, and after growing to manhood went to Antioch and engaged in the mercantile business and continued in that business until a few years ago when he left the store and purchased a farm on which he resided until his death. DEATH
Name: Harriet GATCHELL
======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Harriet GATCHELL >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: Monroe County death records
and The Spirit of Democracy
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> The Spirit of Democracy >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs., Feb. 15, 1917
It is with sadness we note the ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> It is with sadness we note the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 death of our friend and neighbor, Mrs. Harriett Gatchell who was born July 7, 1844, and departed from this life February 5, 1917, being at the time of her death 72 years, six months and 29 days of age. She united with the Baptist Church at this place in the year of 1865. As a friend and neighbor a community would need no better. She was always cheerful and ready and willing to lend a helping hand to those in need, and gave good advice to all. She seemed to have always had her share of disappointments and adversities of this life, but bore them all with Christian grace and fortitude, never murmured or complained but was always willing and submissive to the will of Him who doeth all things well.
Harriet A. WESTBROOK was married ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Harriet A. WESTBROOK was married >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 to Winfield J. GATCHELL December 28, 1865, Born to this union was four children three of which have preceded her to the better world - - Ella and Alzada GATCHELL who died in infancy, and William F. GATCHELL who died at the age of 31 years, in 1905. She leaves to mourn her departure a husband, one daughter, Mrs. Anna MANN, four grandchildren and one great-grandchild. They have the sympathy of the entire community in their sad bereavement, and may they look forward in blessed anticipation and glorious hope of a coming day when they shall meet in that blissful land where sad farewells never come and parting is no more.
The funeral services were conducted in the Methodist Church Wednesday, February 7, by the Rev. M. L. WOTTLING of New Matamoras and interment made in Graysville cemetery.
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> The funeral services were conducted in the Methodist Church Wednesday, February 7, by the Rev. M. L. WOTTLING of New Matamoras and interment made in Graysville cemetery. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> William NALLEY >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, <<<<<<< HEAD Thursday, Mar. 1, 1917
We learn that William NALLEY, ======= Thursday, Mar. 1, 1917
We learn that William NALLEY, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 aged 16 years, son of Mr. and Mrs. Maywood NALLEY of Sycamore Valley, Ohio was killed suddenly February 15, 1917. He was going to see the doctor to get medicine for a cousin who was ill. He rode across the field thinking to save time. When the body was found, the evidence showed that in crossing a stream, his horse jumped and threw him from the saddle. His head struck the frozen ground crushing his skull over the ear, death being instantaneous. He is survived by his parents, four sisters and one brother.

When a heavy Cadillac roadster ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> When a heavy Cadillac roadster >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 which he was driving skidded off the Gallia paved roadway, near Portsmouth, Ohio, Edward V. OBLINGER, aged 33 years, son of John B. OBLINGER, of North Duke and Lemon streets, Portsmouth, Ohio, was injured so badly on Thursday afternoon that he died from his injuries late on Friday, May 4, 1917. The car overturned on Damarin Hill while being driven at a rapid rate and was completely wrecked. Clay from an adjoining shale bank had slid onto the road causing the accident. Another companion, W. P. Scott, 35 years old, of Fort Thomas, Kentucky, was also killed.
The deceased was in the employ of the Chandler Motor company of Portsmouth, Ohio, and was on a business trip when the accident occurred. John GLASER, Sr. for many years a ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> John GLASER, Sr. for many years a >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 resident of Woodsfield, died suddenly Tuesday evening, May 5th, at the home of his daughter, Mrs. Charles REASBECK, in Martins Ferry. Death was due to a complication of diseases incident to old age. Deceased was 83 years of age and was born in Bavaria, Germany. He came to this country when 19 years of age and located in Monroe County, Ohio near Woodsfield. Surviving him are five sons, Joseph, John, Leo and Charles GLASER of Martins Ferry, and Jacob GLASER of Braddock, Pennsylvania and three daughters, Mrs. Charles SCHUMACHER of Woodsfield; Mrs. Charles REASBECK of Martins Ferry, and Sister Angelia of Delano, Minnesota. He has one brother in Germany. Thirty grandchildren and 18 great-grand children also survive. The remains were brought to Woodsfield and taken to the home of his daughter Mrs. Charles Schumacher where they were tenderly cared for until Saturday morning when they were conveyed to the Catholic Church and after services conducted by the Reverend Francis SEEBER were laid to rest in the Church cemetery.

DEATH
Name: John R. BUNTING
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> John R. BUNTING >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: newspaper clipping, 1917
Collection of Gertrude Christman Kahrig
Once more we are called upon to mourn the departure of our beloved ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Once more we are called upon to mourn the departure of our beloved >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 friend John R. BUNTING who was born near Calais, Ohio, September 24, 1888. On Monday, October 29, 1917, he was struck in the stomach with a piece of wood that he was using to attempting to replace a belt on a fly wheel. He was operated on and lived until Wednesday noon when peritonitis set in and resulted in his death. The number of days of his sojourn here being 29 years, one month and seven days. He was the second son of E. M. and Mary L. BUNTING. At an early age he started out to make his mark in the world and he could well say with <<<<<<< HEAD that beloved apostle. I have fought a good fight of faith. He labored in >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Monroe County for a few years and then was employed as bookkeeper for an oil well supply company at Salem, West Virginia until September 1917. On September 18th, he arrived at Norwata, Oklahoma, where he was employed as time and bookkeeper for the Henderson Gasoline Company. Always ready and willing to extend a helping hand he left his work and went to assist an aged gentlemen accomplish what resulted in his untimely death. He graduated with honor from the Clarksburg Business college July 10, 1912; was a member of Nemesis Temple of the shrine of Salem. He also belonged to the other Masonic bodies at Clarksburg, West Virginia being a 32nd degree Mason. He was converted and baptized at Salem, West Virginia some two years ago and has lived a devoted christian life and has lived a devoted life ever since. It can be truly said to him that
None ======= Helvetica;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman";mso-fareast-language:JA'> None >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 knew him but to love him,
Nor <<<<<<< HEAD named him but to praise.
======= named him but to praise. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
He has set an example that is worthy of many followers. He was drafted for service in the United States army in the West Virginia division but had not been examined. He leaves to mourn his early departure father, mother, four brothers, Oscar and Everson BUNTING of Senora, Ohio, Orlin and Otto BUNTING of the home, a lady friend Georgiana CLARK of Salem, West Virginia besides a host of other relatives and friends to whom he was very dear, being preceded by one brother and sister to that peaceful shore.
The remains accompanied by John R. KNAPP, president of the company, arrived Saturday noon and were taken to his home. At 1 p.m. Sunday the Reverend Frank WHARTON of Eldon, Ohio spoke consoling words to the bereaved family, taking for his text the 15th verse of the 106 Psalm, and he gave them their request; but sent leanness into their soul.
All that as mortal of our dear John together with the generous floral contribution was tenderly laid to rest in the Calais cemetery in await the coming of the final judge.
A cousin, D. G. W.

Mr. Crawford was born in Mr. Crawford was born in >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Ireland November 18, 1835, and died at his home on Maple avenue November 25, 1917.
He came to He came to >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">America with his parents when very young and spent his life in Monroe County, Ohio. He was a tanner by trade and at one time was engaged in that business in Beallsville, Ohio, later coming to Woodsfield conducting the same line of business for a number of years. He was known by almost all of the people of Monroe County and enjoyed their confidence, having won their respect because of his honesty and faithfulness toward his fellow man. When Hugh Crawford promised you anything he made good that promise. He was a manly man.
He was united in marriage to Miss ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> He was united in marriage to Miss >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Margaret CRAIG and to this union were born seven children- - four girls and three boys, all of whom are living and all were present when their father passed into the great beyond.

The funeral was held Tuesday and was conducted by the Reverend L. R. LAWTHER of St. Clairsville, Ohio.
May he rest in peace and may the peace of Him whom he trusted for future salvation be a comfort to the bereaved family.

1917
[Source: Wheeling Register, December 28, 1917]
 
CHARLES EVERT READ
 
Funeral services for Charles Evert Read, 45, who died Tuesday evening at 6 o'clock at the home of his sister, Mrs. E. D. Sarver, No. 44 Poplar avenue, Edgewood, were held yesterday afternoon at 2 o'clock at the place of death. Rev. Clement E. Wise, pastor of the Buckley Methodist Episcopal church, officiated. Interment followed in Greenwood.
 
Mr. Read was widely known in this section, a plumber by trade, and was a member of the local union. He was born at Woodsfield, Ohio, July 27, 1872, and had been a resident of this city for about twenty-five years. He was a member of the Methodist church, and is survived by four children, his wife preceding him in death eighteen months, Sarah, Agnes, Elizabeth and Charles, Jr. Also two brothers and two sisters survive, Fred and Frank Read, of eastern Ohio, Mrs. Sarver and Mrs. Fred Ewing, of Mount de Chantal.

Lester Vearl CHRISTMAN son of Mr. and Mrs. John CHRISTMAN, of Calais, Ohio, was born April 3, 1918, and departed his life on June 11, 1918, being at the age of his death ten short weeks. He leaves to mourn his departure his grieving parents, four brothers, Gilbert, Howard, Herbert, and Lee CHRISTMAN; three sisters, Esta, Helen, and Mary CHRISTMAN, all of the home and a host of relatives and friends. Only a few days had been with them but it takes only a few moments to learn to love a baby. It is hard to part with the little ones, but we should remember the words of our <<<<<<< HEAD Savior, Suffer the little children to come unto me, for of such is the kingdom of heaven.

DEATH
Name: Blanche GREENBANK
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Blanche GREENBANK >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs. July 11, 1918
A distressing accident occurred ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> A distressing accident occurred >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 at the home of Mr. Arthur GREENBANK about a mile and a half from Lewisville Saturday morning.
Miss Dorothy Blanche Greenbank ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Miss Dorothy Blanche Greenbank >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 had gone to one of the upstairs rooms for some purpose, and upon opening the door smelled the escaping gas. She located it at an open valve, were the key in some manner had been turned. She turned the key, closing the valve and was leaving the room, when the escaping gas, having reached the hall, was set off by a light burning there. The force of the explosion blew out several windows and the house caught fire, but the flames were extinguished, some furniture and bedding being destroyed, Miss Greenbank assisting heroically in spite of serious injuries.
Blanche GREENBANK, a four-year ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Blanche GREENBANK, a four-year >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 old daughter, was so badly burned that she died Sunday morning. Three other members of the family were also severely burned. Jane GREENBANK, a sister of Mr. Greenbank, was burned so seriously that it is feared it may be necessary to amputate one of her hands. Both hands and arms are badly burned. She was also burned about the breast and on both legs. Two other little daughters received severe injuries from the flames.
Funeral services were held Tuesday at the Buchanan Church over the remains of Blanche GREENBANK and were conducted by the Rev. LASELLES, pastor of the Presbyterian Church.
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Funeral services were held Tuesday at the Buchanan Church over the remains of Blanche GREENBANK and were conducted by the Rev. LASELLES, pastor of the Presbyterian Church. >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

DEATH
Name: Miss Celestia A. CHRISTMAN
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Miss Celestia A. CHRISTMAN >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Source: Monroe County death records
and The Spirit of Democracy
======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> The Spirit of Democracy >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs. Aug. 15, 1918
Collection of Gertrude Christman Kahrig
Miss Celestia A. CHRISTMAN, aged ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Miss Celestia A. CHRISTMAN, aged >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 35 years, daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Andrew G. CHRISTMAN, died at the home of her parents on Sycamore street in Woodsfield, August 7, 1918. She was stricken with typhoid fever several weeks ago and before she recovered from the fever other afflictions of a serious nature set in and rendered her so weak that she was unable to take sufficient nourishment to regain her strength and finally yielded to death. Miss Christman was a young lady of marked intelligence and was well liked by her many acquaintances. Before her illness she had been in the employ of the McFadden store in Wheeling, West Virginia and had a host of friends in that city and also in Bellaire, Ohio. The funeral services were held Friday and interment made in Oaklawn cemetery. Rev. Philip D. LASELLES, pastor of the Presbyterian Church, conducted the services. Deceased leaves father and mother and one brother and a number of other relatives. She had been a faithful member of the Presbyterian Church for many years. Those noticed from a distance in attendance at the funeral were Dr. E. E. SULSBERGER of Bellaire, Mrs. Guss Norteman of Wheeling, Mrs. Dr. William GRIMES of East Liverpool, and Miss Dora BOYER of Bellaire.
======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

DEATH
Name: ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Leander TRUEX
Source: The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs. Aug. 15, 1918
Leander TRUEX, aged 66 years, one ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Leander TRUEX, aged 66 years, one >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 of the best citizens of Woodsfield and a lifelong friend of the writer, died at his home on North main street in Woodsfield August 9, 1918, from a stroke of paralysis. Mr. Truex had not been in good health for several months but had been attending to his farming and other business until a few weeks ago when he suffered a stroke of paralysis which confined him to his room several days. He improved somewhat and was able to come down street a few times after being stricken, but when he made his last visit with us last week it was very plain that he would not recover. Deceased had been an honest upright citizen through life and a consistent member of the Presbyterian Church for many years. He leaves a widow, one brother Anderson TRUEX of Woodsfield route two and one sister Mrs. Minerva RICER of Woodsfield and many acquaintances who will deplore his being called to eternity. The funeral services were held Monday, conducted by his pastor the Rev. Philip D. LASELLES and interment made in Oaklawn cemetery In Woodsfield.
In the same issue of The Spirit ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> In the same issue of The Spirit >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 of Democracy was also an article:
Leander TRUEX, aged 66 years, two months and 25 days, died at his home on North Main street, Woodsfield, on Friday evening, August 9th, 1918, at 11:30. Mr. Truex was born on Jacksons ridge May 15th, 1852, where he lived until about seventeen years ago when he and his wife moved to Woodsfield. He was married to Ellen McCAMMON on July 4th, 1877. As a young man he united with the Methodist Church at Jacksons ridge, afterwards transferring his membership to the Buchanan Presbyterian Church. Mr. Truex leaves to mourn his loss his devoted wife, and one brother and one sister. Funeral services were conducted at the home by the Reverend Philip D. LASELLES on Monday morning, August 11th, at ten oclock. Burial took place in the Oak Lawn cemetery, Woodsfield.

Collection of Gertrude Christman Kahrig
A telegram was received Monday, November 18th, by O. L. THORNBERRY of Jerusalem, Ohio from the Adjutant Generals office that ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> A telegram was received Monday, November 18th, by O. L. THORNBERRY of Jerusalem, Ohio from the Adjutant General s office that >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 his son Sergeant Leland Earl THORNBERRY had died on October 10, 1918, in France from bronchial pneumonia. This is the first known casualty among the boys from this community and coming at this time, after the war had ceased and when all the boys were expected back home, it has cast a very deep gloom over all. Earl, as he was generally called, was a popular and model young man and was a graduate of the Agricultural department of Ohio State university and previous to his entrance into the army held a position as instructor in one of the agricultural colleges of the state. Another son Floyd G. THORNBERRY is in the army, stationed at Fort Hancock, New Jersey.

Edsell T. HAWKS, son of Mr. Homer HAWKS and deceased wife Alma HAWKS, was born in Jerusalem, Ohio, September 17, 1904. He died at Lewisville, R. R. 1 on December 20, 1918, bringing his total age to 14 years, 3 months, and 3 days. He was taken with a slight headache a few days ago, which however turned into violent pains in the spine and head and brought his young days to a rapid close. How often are we not faced by death in this life. We always tremble and totter in fear before it and it is well that we do for it is our greatest enemy. Quickly it is upon us - - to some are given days of thought and penitence before it comes, to others it comes on the wings of eagles. Whether we desire it or not we must accept it. The Materialist accepts it stoically, the atheist with alarm, the thoughtless with fright; the Christian alone can meet it as a challenge with honor, for to him have been given the weapons, against which death cannot survive. It often surprises him that it comes so early <<<<<<< HEAD but his surprise is only the signal to get out his sword of the Spirit and to put on his shield of faith and against such spiritual armor of defense and offense, death cannot and never will prevail. On the cross our Savior showed us what faith, hope and love can do against death and we are true followers if ======= but his surprise is only the signal to get out his sword of the Spirit and to put on his shield of faith and against such spiritual armor of defense and offense, death cannot and never will prevail. On the cross our Savior showed us what faith, hope and love can do against death and we are true followers if >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 we learn from him.
Such were our thoughts when the ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Such were our thoughts when the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 neighbors collected on Sunday afternoon, Dec. 22, 1918, to pay last respects and reverence to the memory of one, who though only 14 years of age, was missed, when he died. He was a quiet boy to the outward observer, but whistling and singing when roaming abroad in solitude. We cannot but praise him when we think that of his fourteen years he had gone seven to Sunday School without voluntarily missing a single service. He was to receive a diploma for this faithfulness. We are sorry that he died before he had received it. He leaves behind many mourning friends and relatives. First among whom is his stepmother, <<<<<<< HEAD who was as good to him as Lincolns ======= who was as good to him as Lincoln s >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 stepmother was to the young Abraham LINCOLN. He was taken to Lewisville after memorial services at the house, from there he was taken to Lowell, Ohio, where he was buried beside his mother.

What <<<<<<< HEAD is death? Tis to be free,
======= is death? Tis to be free, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711
No more to love or hope or fear,
To join th great equality:
All, all alike are humbled there,
The mighty grave wraps, lord and slave.
Nor pride, nor poverty dares come
Within that refuge-house, -the tomb.
Such may, or may not have been ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Such may, or may not have been >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 the thoughts of Henry M. Smith, when he was called from this earth on Friday, December 13, 1918. At least such is the true nature of death. And such is its first function. Naked we are born into this life, and naked we leave it again, stripped of everything material or unspiritual. Nothing enters the great beyond, but what we are at your last breath. If you are a saint, as a saint you embark across the Stygian waters of the unknown; if you are a reprobate sinner, as a reprobate sinner you go across. There is an equality in death and again <<<<<<< HEAD there is not. Equality since we all must share alike deaths bitterness. No ======= there is not. Equality since we all must share alike death s bitterness. No >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 equality since there are some who die a hopeful death and others who die a hopeless death.
Let us hope with all his friends, ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Let us hope with all his friends, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 that our beloved henry M. Smith died a hopeful death. If ever there was a man worthy to be called an optimist, it was he, and I believe, he was an optimist with his last breath too. Can we who are yet among those who are called living hope for a greater recommendation?
The deceased was born December ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> The deceased was born December >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 17, 1884, in Wayne township, Monroe county, Ohio. For many years he resided at Miltonsburg. Among surviving near relatives are his mother, Mrs. Christina C. Claus and one sister, Mrs. Mary E. Dougherty, of Pittsburgh. His father, two brothers and one sister have gone before him to the grave. His father, Michael Smith, died November 22, 1904. Hi brothers, john W. Smith, died March 1, 1908, and George F. Smith, died November 12, 1908. His sister, Mrs. Christina steed, died June 1, 1911.
He was baptized an Evangelical christian by Rev. Samuel Egger. During his early youth he went to school at Duffs College, Pittsburg, He was baptized an Evangelical christian by Rev. Samuel Egger. During his early youth he went to school at Duff s College, Pittsburg, >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 w:st="on">Pa., from where he graduated in 1903. He became a member of faculty of that institution. He resigned his position there and took a more remunerative on with the Waverly Oil Works of Pittsburgh. On account of failing health he was compelled to discontinue this work and retired to his home at miltonsburg, Ohio, where he spent to remainder of his life. As a sufferer he was a rare example. Brave and cheerful. Anyone in the locality can testify to his sunny disposition an spontaneous happy spirits. many, many of us will miss him, now that he is gone to his reward.

Louis STOEHR, aged 57 years, died Monday morning, January 6, 1919. Sunday evening with a neighbor and until at the time of starting home he was in his usual health, but upon starting became ill from some cause and kept on getting worse until about nine oclock Monday morning when he expired. Mr. Stoehr had lived all his life in Woodsfield and was a good citizen, industrious and honest and enjoyed the respect of those with whom he had to do. He leaves a wife and several children. The funeral will be held this Thursday afternoon at 2 oclock and the services will be conducted by the pastor, Reverend A. H. KNIPPING.

Yet to some signing of the Armistice was not as assurance of the safe return of their loved one. On the fourth of February 1919, the household of Mr. and Mrs. Fred CLAUS was shocked and grieved upon the receipt of a letter from Captain Spier containing the sad news that their boy whom they had all thought well and contented in Grancem had died four weeks before.

This however was to be his final resting place. The remains were removed from their first resting place and brought to his native country. Name: Herman ACKERMAN

Source: Newspaper clipping and
St. JohnsSt. John s>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 style='font-family:Helvetica;mso-bidi-font-family:"Times New Roman"; mso-fareast-language:JA'> Church records, February 1919

Herman ACKERMAN, the subject of ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Herman ACKERMAN, the subject of >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 this sketch, was born on the 15th day of February, 1837, in Landefeld, near Spangenburg Gur-Hessan, Germany. His parents being interested more in his spiritual than in his material welfare had him confirmed in the Christian faith while yet in the Fatherland on May 21st, 1851. In the year 1857, on the 11th day of April, he left the Fatherland and sailed to America and landed in Wheeling, West Virginia, on July 22nd of the same year. On March 16, 1862, he was united in marriage to Mary NIESZ, and to this union seven children was born, three sons and four daughters. Anna, the eldest of the children, preceded him to the better land on March 1, 1896. He leaves to mourn, his devoted wife and the following children, John ACKERMAN near home; Henry ACKERMAN of Somerton, Ohio; Benjamin ACKERMAN, of Donora, Pennsylvania; Mrs. Jacob CHRISTMAN, near home; Mrs. John CHRISTMAN, of Calais, Ohio; and Mrs. John SEEBACH, of Alliance. Also twenty-nine grandchildren and ten great grandchildren. The first ten years of their married life was spent in Benwood and Wheeling, West Virginia. In March, 1872, they moved from Wheeling to Ohio near Monroefield on the farm known as the Jacob BERTRAM farm; here they lived dividing their joys and sorrows till in the fall of 1889, when they moved to the farm on which he died, which was on the 27th day of February, 1919, being at the time of his death 82 years and 12 days old. In November last he took sick with that dreaded disease pneumonia from which he never recovered sinking gradually until death relieved him. During his illness he was tenderly cared for by his loving wife and children and grandchildren, but more especially by two grandchildren, Clara BINTZ and Viola BINTZ, who were constantly at his bedside doing all that loving hands could do to restore him to health, but to no avail, He was laid away to await the resurrection morn on <<<<<<< HEAD Sunday, March 2nd, in the St. Johns Middle Church cemetery, followed by a large concourse of friends and relatives, amid ======= Sunday, March 2nd, in the St. John s Middle Church cemetery, followed by a large concourse of friends and relatives, amid >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 beautiful floral offerings. The funeral was conducted by his former pastor, the Reverend Paul SALESKE, of Chicago, Illinois.

On February 18, 1919, the pure ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> On February 18, 1919, the pure >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 and gentle spirit of Mrs. Ellen TRUEX was called from this world to the celestial home above, being in her 73rd year. The subject of this sketch, formerly Miss Ellen McCAMMON, was born in the year 1846, on a farm now the home of her brother, Alexander McCAMMON, of near Kerr Station. She was the youngest daughter of Robert and Jane McCAMMON, and one of a family of six children of which the oldest brother, Alexander, is the only surviving member. Two brothers, Robert and Samuel, and two sister, Mrs. Jane BROWN and Mrs. Sarah STIMPERT having preceded her to that hem where there is no parting and no more good byes said. Mrs. Truex was formerly one of Monroe Countys ======= w:st="on">Monroe County s >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 progressive school teachers and will always be kindly remembered by many of the middle aged men and women of today for whom she did so much by always setting a good example of patriotism and morality. She always had a word of welcome for all who came to visit her home and there was nothing gave her more pleasure than to have her friends around her enjoying a social chat with those near and dear to her. She will be sadly missed by her many friends and relatives.

Mr. Pfalzgraf was an industrious farmer and the farm became a valuable one, and especially in the last few years when it was found to have exceptional deposits of coal under it.
Mr. and Mrs. Pfalzgraf raised a ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Mr. and Mrs. Pfalzgraf raised a >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 family of twelve children, all of whom with his widow are living except two, William PFALZGRAF, who died at the age of five years and George PFALZGRAF, who was killed in an accident in Pittsburgh several years ago. In office he used the same practical common sense and good judgment that characterized his own business transactions.
For the thirty years preceding his ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> For the thirty years preceding his >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 death he had been a member of Clarington Lodge No. 346 K. of P. and was a strong advocate of the high principles of that fraternal organization.

In personality, Mr. Pfalzgraf was open hearted, kind and friendly and many young people long since in homes of their own remember the good times the hospitable home afforded years ago.
For the past years, Mr. Pfalzgraf ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> For the past years, Mr. Pfalzgraf >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 had been in rather poor health, yet considering years and infirmities his active will refused to submit where a man of less stamina would have yielded. Mr. Henry SCHUTTY, an aged and retired business man of Clarington, Ohio passed away at his home here Friday evening at about 7:30 oclock, after a lingering illness. He was taken ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Mr. Henry SCHUTTY, an aged and retired business man of Clarington, Ohio passed away at his home here Friday evening at about 7:30 o clock, after a lingering illness. He was taken >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 to his bed about six weeks ago when he suffered a slight stroke of paralysis. His death had been expected for several days but came as a severe shock to the surviving relatives. Mr. Schutty was a pioneer of the town having engaged in business here about the year 1850 and continued until a few years ago, since which time he had been living a retired life. He was in the 89th year of his age and is survived by four daughters, his wife Elisabeth SCHUTTY, and one daughter having preceded him to the grave several years ago. Funeral services while not complete will likely be held Sunday with services at the Evangelical church with burial in the family lot in Clarington cemetery.

In 1879 Mr. Hines was received into the fellowship of the Church of Christ at Hartshorn and when the church at Clear Frok was organized, he was selected as one of the elders, which position he held at the time of his death. He was a farmer all his life, and his ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> He was a farmer all his life, and his >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 application and ability made him a successful one.

Source: The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs., Mar. 31, 1921
Brief announcements of the sudden ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Brief announcements of the sudden >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 death of Mr. Harry O. GOODRICH, former editor and proprietor of The Monroe Courier, and eldest son of Charles H. GOODRICH, well known at one time as editor of The Monroe Gazette. Harry, it seems had been in poor health for some time. He had been working on a paper near his home at Hot Springs, Arkansas, with his son, James GOODRICH. He became worse and his son started home to Hot Springs with him, but he died of apoplexy on the train. His remains were taken to Nashville, Tennessee for burial, where most of his children lived. His death occurred March 16, 1921. He leaves a wife and several children.

He enlisted under the stars and ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> He enlisted under the stars and >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 stripes, October 5, 1861, and was mustered in as a private to serve three years in Company K, 62nd Ohio Volunteer Infantry under Captain William DOUGHERTY, Henry R. WEST and John D. KENNEDY. His regiment left for Cumberland, Maryland on January 17, 1862, and was attached to 2nd Brig. Landers Division, Army of the Potomac in March 1862. With his company he advanced in March 1862, to Winchester, Virginia and from that time on until honorably discharged on October 26, 1864, participated in many of the hardest fought battles of the great was, with a very short hospital record.

Catharine Fedorchak's Family Research in Monroe Co., Vol. II, Part II: "In the 1860 census Henry Morris can be found on page 132, Family No. 619. His three oldest sons are on page 514 in Wayne Township, families 1061 - Wilson, married to Hannah Jane LONG. . . Also on page 38 of this volume: "Wilson Morris died in Monroe Co. at the age of 94 and some of his descendants live near Rinard's Mills on Route 26." Elsie Bonam gave me a handwritten receipt signed by Wilson: "August 28th 1860 Received of H. G. Morris three hundred and seventy-five dollars to pay on land. Elsie Bonam's notes: "Wilson married Hannah Jane Long about 1858. She died November 16, 1878, at the age of 38 years and 23 days, believed to be the daughter of Jacob Long and Hannah. No marriage record is available of Wilson Morris and Hannah Jane Long because several fires in Monroe County, Ohio." Application to Probate Filed: Wilson Morris deceased July 13th. Woodsfield, Ohio, Thursday, July 7, 1921
Philip L. ULLMAN, prosperous farmer ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Philip L. ULLMAN, prosperous farmer >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 and stock dealer of Harriettsville, aged 71 years 11 months and 5 days, drowned Wednesday evening about 9:45 in Duck Creek, a quarter of a mile from his home, when the horse he was driving backed the buggy in which he was riding over the bank throwing him out and pinning him beneath its weight. Thus trapped Mr. Ullman lost his life in less than three feet of water. His body was recovered from the stream a short time afterward by persons summoned to the scene by the <<<<<<< HEAD victims wife who was the only witness to the accident.
Mr. Ullman had been away from home ======= victim s wife who was the only witness to the accident.
Mr. Ullman had been away from home >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 all day buying cattle and looking after other business. When almost home he was met by his wife who was attempting to get him in the rig when the horse began to back. Mr. Ullman was unable to stop the horse and it went over a six-foot embankment near the home of W. A. SCHAFER.
On January 28, 1875, he was united ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> On January 28, 1875, he was united >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 in marriage to Theresa E. UNGER. To this union eight children were born, two of whom have gone before.

In her 17th year she came to America and settled in Wheeling, West Virginia. In 1855, she was united in marriage to Godfrey HYER and in 1864 they came to Hannibal, where she has since resided and proved herself a neighbor and friend, and loved by all who knew her. Formerly she was a member of the Evangelical church, but in 1897, she joined the German M. E. church and remained a faithful and active member until her death. Her husband and three children preceded her and the following children survive: Mrs. Carrie NEUENSCHWANDER of Cleveland, John HYER of Akron, Ohio; Henry HYER of Lima, Ohio, and David HYER of Wheeling. The deceased is also survived by 11 grandchildren and 8 great grand children. Her funeral was held on Sunday afternoon and the services were largely attended and were conducted at her late home by her pastor, Rev. E. A. RODAHAFFER, and interment was made in the family lot in the Harter cemetery. There were beautiful offerings.

Source: newspaper article, Oct. 1921
Provided by Eloise Lumbatis January
Once more the angel of death has ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Once more the angel of death has >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 visited the community of Neffs, Ohio, and taken from its midst a devoted wife and mother, Mrs. Anna Wise, daughter of Sebastian and Susie Kelley. She was born August 4, 1864, near Lewisville, Ohio, and died October 24, 1921, at her home at Neffs, Belmont county, Ohio. She was united in marriage to Peter Wise July 18, 1886. To this union nine children were born: Willie, Carl, Lando, Charles, Estella, Luna, Mary, Esther, and another son who died in infancy.
She is one who will be sadly missed ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> She is one who will be sadly missed >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 from her home and friends as her life was one of usefulness and good deeds wherever she was present. At the early age of 14 years she became a member of the M. E. church at Bracken Chapel, Summerfield charge. Later she moved her name to Neffs, where she remained a faithful and consistent member until death. She was a willing worker in the church, Sunday School and W. C. T. U.
The afternoon preceding her death she spent in visiting her children. At. 6 oclock in the evening she was suddenly stricken with paralysis. At. 9 oclock she was cold in death. The record of her life is finished. Not a line need be censored. She has fought a good fight and has gone to her heavenly home where sorrow never comes and we shall never say Goodbye.

MEDIS, John Calvin
Active members Church of Christ, Paden City, ======= style='mso-spacerun:yes'> Active members Church of Christ, Paden City, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 W. VA.
** IN MEMORIAM**
"OBITUARY"
By Ira C. Moore, (old newspaper clipping)
 
MEDIS-John Calvin, was born into this world in Monroe County, Ohio on Oct. 1, 1843, and died at his brother's in Paden City, W. VA., October 24, 1921, being aged 78 years and twenty-three days. At the age of eighteen he was born again under the preaching of the documented and honored Nathan W. Cramblett and according to the testimony of those who knew him, he ever lived a faithful Christian life. His late home was in New Brighton, PA, but recently went on a visit to his native community and conducted the worship only about two weeks before his death. A few years ago he sojourned in Paden City for a time and formed many acquaintances and made a good record by attending the worship there. Fifty years ago he was married to Miss Catherine Richner and to them were born five girls and three boys. He came to Paden City to visit his brother and died there, this writer was called to cover the funeral on Tuesday, October 25. The worn out body of Bro. Medis was laid to rest in the cemetery near to await the judgment day.
*****
"The funeral services were held in a small country church, John C. Medis remains were not brought back to PA. for burial.

Hers was the hand to help the needy and none were ever turned away from her door hungry, but her earthly life is spent and God has called her home.

It is with sadness we are called ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> It is with sadness we are called >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 upon to note the departure of our friend and neighbor, James Jacob NEUHARDT, son of John Michael and Mary Catherine SCHAUB NEUHART. John Michael died September 11, 1909, in Monroe County, Ohio and Mary Catherine died in 1890. James Jacob was born August 1, 1857, at the Neuhardt homestead in Summit township, Monroe County, Ohio, and departed this life July 9, 1922, at the Good Samaritan Hospital, Zanesville, Ohio. On Sunday, November 12, 1885, he was married to Miss Lucetta BINTZ. To this union were born five children of which two daughters, Clara Lucetta and Harriett Magdelina gone to the world beyond. Harriett Magdelina NEUHARDT died March 3, 1911.
Just a week before he passed away he ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Just a week before he passed away he >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 seemed to be enjoying life as usual when suddenly on Sunday afternoon, July 2, he was stricken ill. His case was placed in the physician and upon his advice it was deemed best to go to the hospital where he was placed in the hands of the surgeons. Although his condition was serious they thought it best to try the gallstone operation. This for a time seemed to be successful, then uremic poisoning set in which resulted in his death. Before he started to the hospital, he expressed the thought that perhaps he might never return but was ready to face death. He was accompanied by his faithful wife, who at his request never left him until the end came.
On Sunday afternoon, July 2, the ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> On Sunday afternoon, July 2, the >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 body was brought from Zanesville to the home to await the funeral services which were held in the German M. E. Church near Monroefield, Ohio, on Wednesday morning, July 12, and the remains were laid to rest in the cemetery therein the presence of a large number of friends and relatives. The services were conducted by the Reverend Theodore LAGFEMANN of Hopkins, Michigan, a former pastor and friend.
He was a kind husband and devoted father and he will be sadly missed in the home and in the community in which he has spent his life, but we can only say Thy will, Lord, and not ours be done.
He leaves to mourn his loss, his ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> He was a kind husband and devoted father and he will be sadly missed in the home and in the community in which he has spent his life, but we can only say Thy will, Lord, and not ours be done.

Names: Mr. Harry JOHNSTON
and Miss Nellie KELLER
Source: and Miss Nellie KELLER
Source: >>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 style='mso-bidi-font-style:normal'>The Spirit of Democracy
Woodsfield, Ohio, Thurs., Jan. 11, 1923
Married, on December 26, 1923, at the home of W. M. JOHNSTON, the Grooms father, Miss Nellie Keller of ======= style='mso-tab-count:1'> Married, on December 26, 1923, at the home of W. M. JOHNSTON, the Groom s father, Miss Nellie Keller of >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Graysville, Ohio and Mr. Harry Johnston of Sycamore Valley. The marriage ceremony was performed by J. F. CLIFT, Esq., and was a grand affair, which made them man and wife. After the marriage ceremony congratulations were extended to the bride and groom, after which they were marched with their friends to the dining room where they were seated around the table, loaded down with all that the appetite could wish for and of which all partook freely except J. f. CLIFT, who failed to have capacity to satisfy his appetite and James KNOWLTON had to be persuaded to leave the table for fear of overeating after supper. They were given an old-fashioned serenade by a large crowd which had gathered, and who all extended congratulations to the happy married couple. Then came the treat which consisted of candy, pie, cake and stogies. Among the guests were Mr. and Mrs. Chris UNGER, Mr. and Mrs. Charles MASSIE, Ula, Garnet, Vera and Garold UNGER, Clarence KNOWLTON, Mr. and Mrs. James KNOWLTON, Orian KNOWLTON, F. LAW, Mr. and Mrs. Gus MARSHALL, Mr. and Mrs. C. H. ULLMAN, Mr. and Mrs. G. B. McFADDEN, Harold BURKHART, Mr. and Mrs. John BURKHART, John F. CLIFT, Esq., Mr. and Mrs. W. M. JOHNSTON. After distribution of presents, which were many and appropriate, the guests were entertained by music, vocal and instrumental, with Miss Hattie JOHNSTON and Mr. Charles MASSIE at the piano. After which the crowd dispersed reporting a good time.
-One Who Was There
======= style='mso-tab-count:2'> -One Who Was There >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711

This finally caused his unexpected death. On Tuesday he underwent an operation for this which proved unsuccessful. He was called to his reward February 1, 1923, and is survived by his wife, Louise; two sons, Clarence and Elmer Feldner; three daughters, Luella, Anna Louise and Lucille Kathryn; three brothers, a sister and a great number of relatives and friends.

Her husband, Louis SULSBERGER, died two years ago. The children present at the funeral were, C. C. SULSBERGER of Climbing Hill, Iowa; Mrs. George GRAHAM of Bridgeport, Ohio; Mrs. Lee BRIGGS living near Woodsfield and F. O. and F. L. SULSBERGER of Woodsfield.

He was engaged in the Mense-Argonne, October 1-12, 1918, and again on the same <<<<<<< HEAD section November 5-8. From November 17, ======= section November 5-8. From November 17, >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 1918, to August 21, 1919, he was with the army of occupation in Germany. He reached the United States September 5, 1919, and was discharged at Camp Meade, September 24, 1919. From that time on he spent nearly two years in the service hospitals returning to his home last April. He was born July 22, 1888, and leaves a father, three sisters and two brothers.
